1 Introduction

1.1 Basic statistis and projects in R course

The course Basic statistics and projects in R (BSPR) is part of the Public Health Sciences Course Program (PHS) at the University of Bern. I attended this course from 05.06.2023 to 09.06.2023.

This is my final report for the BSPR course.

1.2 Fifth Dutch growth study

For this report I will use data from the Fifth Dutch growth study (SchÃ¶nbeck et al., 2011). This cross-sectional study was conducted in the Netherlands from 2008 to 2009 and collected body height and body weight of approximately 10â000 children aged 0-21 years.

In this report I would like to assess the following questions:

  • Does body height differ between boys and girls who participated in this study?
  • Does body weight differ between boys and girls who participated in this study?

2 Data

2.1 Libraries

For this project I will use the following libraries:

Code 
library(mice)
library(tidyverse)
library(unibeCols)
library(gtsummary)
library(rstatix)
library(knitr)

2.2 Import data

An anonymized dataset of the Fifth Dutch growth study can be directly loaded in R with the package mice:

Code 
data <- data.frame(fdgs)

2.3 Clean data

I clean the dataset by selecting the variables âidâ, âregâ, âageâ, âsexâ, âhgtâ, âwgtâ and renaming them as âidâ, âregionâ, âageâ, âsexâ, âheightâ, âweightâ:

Code 
data <- data %>% 
  select('id', 'reg', 'age', 'sex', 'hgt', 'wgt') %>%
  rename('region'='reg', 'height'='hgt', 'weight' = 'wgt')

3 Results

3.1 Characteristics of the study population

TableÂ 1 summarizes the main characteristics of the study population. There were 4â829 boys and 5â201 girls participating in the study. The median age was 7.9 years for boys and 8.4 years for girls. The median height was 131 cm for boys and 132 cm for girls. The median weight was 27 kg for boys and 28 kg for girls.

Code 
tbl_characteristics <- data %>%   
  select('age','sex','height','weight') %>% 
  tbl_summary(by=sex,
              missing="no",
              label = list(
      age ~ "Age in years",
      height ~ "Height in cm",
      weight ~ "Weight in kg")
    )

3.2 Body height in boys and girls

3.2.1 Descriptive statistics

FigureÂ 1 shows the height of the children in dependency of age grouped by sex.

Code 
fig_height <- ggplot(data, mapping=aes(x=age, y=height, color = sex))+
  geom_point()+
  theme_minimal()+
  xlab("Age in years")+
  ylab("Height in cm")+
  scale_colour_manual(values=c("boy" = unibeIce(), "girl"= unibeRed()))

fig_height

From FigureÂ 1 we can see that the height increases with age. Therefore, i construct age groups with 2 yearly steps and then look at the mean height in these groups. TableÂ 2 shows the number of participants n, the mean height and the standard deviation of the height for the different age groups and sexes.

Code 
data$age_cat<-cut(data$age,seq(from=0,to=22,by=2), right=FALSE)

tbl_height <- data %>%
  group_by(age_cat, sex) %>%
  summarise(n=n(),
                 mean=mean(height,na.rm=TRUE),
                 sd = sd(height,na.rm=TRUE)
                 ) %>% 
  mutate(mean = round(mean, digits=3),
         sd = round(sd, digits=3)) %>% 
  rename("Age group (years)" = "age_cat", "mean (cm)" = "mean", "sd (cm)" = "sd")
  

tbl_height
TableÂ 2: Body height by age group and sex

FigureÂ 2 shows boxplots of the height for the different age groups. We start to see a difference in height at the age group [14,16), where girls start to be smaller than boys. To test whether this difference in height could be due to chance I will calculate confidence intervals and p-values in the next section.

Code 
ggplot(data,mapping=aes(x=age_cat, y=height, fill=sex, color=sex)) +
  geom_boxplot()+
  theme_bw()+
  scale_colour_manual(values=c("boy" = unibeIce(), "girl"= unibeRed()))+
  scale_fill_manual(values=c("boy" = unibeIce(), "girl"= unibeRed()))+
  #facet_grid(cols=vars(sex))+
  xlab("Age group in years")+
  ylab("Height in cm")

3.2.2 Analytic statistics

I first test for normality in the different age groups. FigureÂ 3 shows QQ-Plots of the height in the different age groups with a theoretical normal distribution.

Code 
ggplot(data, mapping=aes(sample=height))+
  geom_qq_line(distribution = stats::qnorm)+
  geom_qq()+
  theme_bw()+
  scale_colour_manual(values=c("boy" = unibeIce(), "girl"= unibeRed()))+
  scale_fill_manual(values=c("boy" = unibeIce(), "girl"= unibeRed()))+
  facet_grid(cols=vars(sex), rows=vars(age_cat))+
  ylab("Sample quantile: height in cm")+
  xlab("Theoretical quantile: standard deviation score")

The QQ plots show that most age groups have a nearly normal distributed body height. The QQ plot for the age group [0,2) of boys and girls shows some deviation of the sample from the theoretical normal distribution. Therefore, I run the Shapiro-Wilk test to test for normality in this age group, see TableÂ 3.

Code 
data %>%
  filter(age_cat=="[0,2)") %>% 
  group_by(sex) %>% 
  shapiro_test(height) %>% 
  mutate(statistic = round(statistic,digits=3))
TableÂ 3: Shapiro-Wilk test in the age group [0,2)

The low p-values resulting from the Shapiro-Wilk test suggest that the height in these to groups does not follow a normal distribution. Because the sample size in this age group is high for both boys and girls (see TableÂ 2), I donât exclude this group. I will not perform a transformation of the height to ensure comparability across the different age groups.

I assess the difference of the mean height between boys and girls for the different age groups. For this I use a t-test with the null-hypothesis that there is no difference. The results are shown in TableÂ 4. When boys are bigger the difference is positive, and when girls are bigger the difference is negative. The confidence interval is a 95%-confidence interval.

Code 
tbl_height_t_test <- data %>%
  group_by(age_cat) %>% 
  t_test(formula = height~sex, conf.level=0.95, detailed=TRUE) %>% 
  select(age_cat,estimate,conf.low,conf.high,p) %>%
  mutate(estimate = round(estimate,digits=3),
         conf.low = round(conf.low, digits = 3),
         conf.high = round(conf.high, digits= 3),
         p = round(p, digits=4)) %>% 
  rename("Age group (years)"="age_cat", "Difference of mean height (cm)"="estimate","Lower confidence"="conf.low", "Upper confidence"="conf.high","p-Value"="p")
  
kable(tbl_height_t_test)
TableÂ 4: T-test for difference in mean height between boys and girls by age group
Age group (years) Difference of mean height (cm) Lower confidence Upper confidence p-Value
[0,2) 1.295 0.502 2.087 0.0014
[2,4) 0.660 -0.145 1.465 0.1080
[4,6) 1.562 0.446 2.679 0.0062
[6,8) 1.689 0.653 2.725 0.0014
[8,10) 1.364 0.430 2.298 0.0043
[10,12) -0.464 -1.391 0.464 0.3270
[12,14) 0.571 -0.607 1.750 0.3410
[14,16) 7.981 6.950 9.012 0.0000
[16,18) 11.817 10.658 12.975 0.0000
[18,20) 14.002 12.827 15.177 0.0000
[20,22) 12.666 11.128 14.203 0.0000

The difference in body height in lower age groups is small compared to higher age groups. In lower age groups there are some tendencies that boys are approximately 1.5 cm bigger. For the age groups ([0,2),[4,6), [6,8),[8,10)) this difference has a p-value of < 0.01 and thus is unlikely to be only due to chance.

In the higher age groups ([14,16) and higher) the boys are 8 - 14 cm bigger than the girls and the results get highly significant. Hence, we can conclude that boys are bigger than girls, with big differences starting at 14 to 16 years.

3.3.2 Analytic statistics

I first test for normality in the different age groups. FigureÂ 6 shows QQ-Plots of the weight in the different age groups.

Code 
ggplot(data, mapping=aes(sample=weight))+
  geom_qq_line(distribution = stats::qnorm)+
  geom_qq()+
  theme_bw()+
  scale_colour_manual(values=c("boy" = unibeIce(), "girl"= unibeRed()))+
  scale_fill_manual(values=c("boy" = unibeIce(), "girl"= unibeRed()))+
  facet_grid(cols=vars(sex), rows=vars(age_cat))+
  ylab("Sample quantile: weight in kg")+
  xlab("Theoretical quantile: standard deviation score")

The QQ plots show that the body weight in various age groups is not normally distributed. Because the sample size is large in all of the groups I will not use a transformation to achieve normally distributed body weights.

I assess the difference of the mean weight between boys and girls for the different age groups. Again, I perform a t-test with the null-hypothesis that there is no difference. The results are shown in TableÂ 6. When boys are heavier the difference is positive, and when girls are heavier the difference is negative. The confidence interval is a 95%-confidence interval.

Code 
tbl_weight_t_test <- data %>%
  group_by(age_cat) %>% 
  t_test(formula = weight~sex, conf.level=0.95, detailed=TRUE) %>% 
  select(age_cat,estimate,conf.low,conf.high,p) %>%
  mutate(estimate = round(estimate,digits=3),
         conf.low = round(conf.low, digits = 3),
         conf.high = round(conf.high, digits= 3),
         p=round(p,digits=4)) %>% 
  rename("Age group (years)"="age_cat", "Difference of mean weight (kg)"="estimate","Lower confidence"="conf.low", "Upper confidence"="conf.high","p-Value"="p")
  
kable(tbl_weight_t_test)

[0,2) 0.507 0.305 0.710 0.0000
[2,4) 0.243 -0.040 0.526 0.0921

Similar to the body height, the difference in body weight is smaller in lower age groups compared to higher age groups. In the lowest age group there is a difference of 0.5 kg with a low p-value.

In the age group [10,12) the girls are 1 kg heavier than the boys.

In the higher age groups ([14,16) and higher) the difference in the mean weight is bigger and the results get highly significant with very low p-values. Boys are 4 kg heavier in the age group [14,16) and 12.5 kg heavier in the age group [20,22). Hence, we can conclude that boys are heavier than girls, starting at around 14-16 years.

4 Discussion

First, I wanted to answer the question whether boys are bigger than girls in the Fifth Dutch growth study. The results suggests that boys are bigger than girls, but only starting at ages 14-16.

Second, I wanted to assess whether boys are heavier than girls in this study. We see that boys are heavier than girls, but again only starting at ages 14-16.

# Introduction

## Basic statistis and projects in R course

The course Basic statistics and projects in R ([BSPR](https://zuw.me/kurse/dt.php?kid=4474)) is part of the Public Health Sciences Course Program ([PHS](https://zuw.me/kurse/index.php?base=phs-ispm&set_hl=en)) at the [University of Bern](https://www.unibe.ch). I attended this course from 05.06.2023 to 09.06.2023.

This is my final report for the BSPR course.

## Fifth Dutch growth study
For this report I will use data from the Fifth Dutch growth study ([SchÃ¶nbeck et al., 2011](https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0027608)). This cross-sectional study was conducted in the Netherlands from 2008 to 2009 and collected body height and body weight of approximately 10'000 children aged 0-21 years.

In this report I would like to assess the following questions:

- Does body height differ between boys and girls who participated in this study?
- Does body weight differ between boys and girls who participated in this study?

### Analytic statistics

I first test for normality in the different age groups.
@fig-qq-height shows QQ-Plots of the height in the different age groups with a theoretical normal distribution.

```{r}
ggplot(data, mapping=aes(sample=height))+
```

The QQ plots show that most age groups have a nearly normal distributed body height. The QQ plot for the age group [0,2) of boys and girls shows some deviation of the sample from the theoretical normal distribution. Therefore, I run the Shapiro-Wilk test to test for normality in this age group, see @tbl-shapiro-height.


```{r}

  mutate(statistic = round(statistic,digits=3))
  
```

The low p-values resulting from the Shapiro-Wilk test suggest that the height in these to groups does not follow a normal distribution. Because the sample size in this age group is high for both boys and girls (see @tbl-height), I don't exclude this group. I will not perform a transformation of the height to ensure comparability across the different age groups.

I assess the difference of the mean height between boys and girls for the different age groups. For this I use a t-test with the null-hypothesis that there is no difference. The results are shown in @tbl-t-test-height. When boys are bigger the difference is positive, and when girls are bigger the difference is negative. The confidence interval is a 95%-confidence interval.

```{r}

#| tbl-cap: T-test for difference in mean height between boys and girls by age group
#| tbl-colwidths: [13,35,20,20,12]

tbl_height_t_test <- data %>%
  group_by(age_cat) %>% 
  t_test(formula = height~sex, conf.level=0.95, detailed=TRUE) %>% 
  select(age_cat,estimate,conf.low,conf.high,p) %>%
  mutate(estimate = round(estimate,digits=3),
         conf.low = round(conf.low, digits = 3),
         conf.high = round(conf.high, digits= 3),
         p = round(p, digits=4)) %>% 
  rename("Age group (years)"="age_cat", "Difference of mean height (cm)"="estimate","Lower confidence"="conf.low", "Upper confidence"="conf.high","p-Value"="p")
  
kable(tbl_height_t_test)
```

The difference in body height in lower age groups is small compared to higher age groups. In lower age groups there are some tendencies that boys are approximately 1.5 cm bigger. For the age groups ([0,2),[4,6),
[6,8),[8,10)) this difference has a p-value of < 0.01 and thus is unlikely to be only due to chance.

In the higher age groups ([14,16) and higher) the boys are 8 - 14 cm bigger than the girls and the results get highly significant. Hence, we can conclude that boys are bigger than girls, with big differences starting at 14 to 16 years.

```{r}
#| warning: false
#| label: tbl-t-test-weight
#| tbl-cap: T-test for difference in mean weight between boys and girls by age group
#| tbl-colwidths: [13,35,20,20,12]

tbl_weight_t_test <- data %>%
  group_by(age_cat) %>% 
  t_test(formula = weight~sex, conf.level=0.95, detailed=TRUE) %>% 
  select(age_cat,estimate,conf.low,conf.high,p) %>%
  mutate(estimate = round(estimate,digits=3),
         conf.low = round(conf.low, digits = 3),
         conf.high = round(conf.high, digits= 3),
         p=round(p,digits=4)) %>% 
  rename("Age group (years)"="age_cat", "Difference of mean weight (kg)"="estimate","Lower confidence"="conf.low", "Upper confidence"="conf.high","p-Value"="p")
  
kable(tbl_weight_t_test)
```

Similar to the body height, the difference in body weight is smaller in lower age groups compared to higher age groups. In the lowest age group there is a difference of 0.5 kg with a low p-value.

In the age group [10,12) the girls are 1 kg heavier than the boys.

In the higher age groups ([14,16) and higher) the difference in the mean weight is bigger and the results get highly significant with very low p-values. Boys are 4 kg heavier in the age group [14,16) and 12.5 kg heavier in the age group [20,22). Hence, we can conclude that boys are heavier than girls, starting at around 14-16 years.

# Discussion

First, I wanted to answer the question whether boys are bigger than girls in the Fifth Dutch growth study. The results suggests that boys are bigger than girls, but only starting at ages 14-16.

Second, I wanted to assess whether boys are heavier than girls in this study. We see that boys are heavier than girls, but again only starting at ages 14-16.
